<p>This is how many middle-class households stall. The problem is rarely one reckless indulgence. It is fragmentation. Income arrives in large visible chunks; spending expands in small forgettable increments. A raise feels meaningful. The habits it funds feel trivial. Historically, that is why higher salaries often fail to produce wealth. Consumption rises almost automatically unless someone actively resists it.</p>
